T1  - Immunization as a maxmin strategy: A new look
AU  - Prisman, Eliezer Z.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 10
IS  - 4
SP  - 491
EP  - 509
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/12/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(86)80002-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426686800024
AB  - The purpose of this paper is to broaden the analysis of immunization when it is viewed as amaxmin strategy. Several results are demonstrated which provide a new interpretation of maxmin strategy by using a more general theory of Lagrangians. We clarify the exact assumptions required for the duration strategy and the maxmin strategy to be equivalent in a world with taxes. It is shown that in a world with taxes the immunization strategy requires the portfolio to satisfy a constraint about the bond to be included, in addition to the duration constraint.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - An application of the cox proportional hazards model to bank failure
AU  - Lane, William R.
AU  - Looney, Stephen W.
AU  - Wansley, James W.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 10
IS  - 4
SP  - 511
EP  - 531
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/12/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(86)80003-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426686800036
AB  - The purpose of this study is to present the Cox proportional hazards model and to apply this model to the prediction of bank failures. The Cox model, which has been used extensively in biomedical applications, has not been previously employed in the finance literature. The principal advantage of the Cox model over other classification techniques is that it models the expected time to failure. Results of the study indicate that total classification accuracy of the Cox model is similar to that of discriminant analysis, although the Cox model produces somewhat lower type I errors. In a comparison of actual and predicted times to failure, the Cox model tends to identify bankruptcies prior to the actual failure date.
ER  - 

